The legendary special force was tasked with creating havoc behind enemy lines through sabotage and slaughter and laid the foundation for the U.S. navy SEALS and the modern day special forces in Canada. 

The troop were so feared by the Nazis that they earned the nickname the 'Devil's Brigade' because of their painted faces and stealth tactics. 

On Tuesday, Devil's Brigade veteran Eugene Guttierez Jr, of Texas, accepted the Gold Medal on behalf of his comrades, living and passed. 

'Guess what? They delivered,' he said, as he accepted the highest Congressional honor for  civilians.

Guttierez enlisted in the Army in 1941 and went on to fight with the Devil's Brigade in the coastal city of Anzio, Italy before helping liberate Rome.

House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi called the brigade members 'heroes' who 'helped free the world of tyranny'. 

Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Kentucky, also weighed in to toast the brigade's special set of skills that helped secure Allied victory. 

